        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1667.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 13 April [1855]</ref>, n. 1.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Possibly the two catalogues issued in 1855 by John Cattell, seedsman in Westerham, Kent, which are preserved in DAR 46.2: 1–2. They are heavily annotated by CD in ink and pencil. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1667.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 13 April [1855]</ref>, n. 6. There is no evidence that Hooker marked the lists.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_408.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Miles Joseph Berkeley</ref> also sent a notice to the <hi rend="italic">Gardeners’ Chronicle and Agricultural Gazette</hi>, no. 17, 28 April 1855, p. 278. In his notice, Berkeley commented on CD’s request for information and described experiments carried out by immersing bags of seeds in fresh sea-water. These experiments, carried out by a friend, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2322.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Henry Hoffman</ref> of Margate, were further reported in the <hi rend="italic">Gardeners’ Chronicle and Agricultural Gazette</hi>, no. 35, 1 September 1855, p. 580.</note>
